
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:02,334
(man) The sharks are back

00:00:02,334 --> 00:00:04,670
in an all-new season
of "Shark Tank,"

00:00:04,670 --> 00:00:07,139
where hopeful entrepreneurs
from across the country

00:00:07,139 --> 00:00:09,875
dream of a chance
to secure an investment

00:00:09,875 --> 00:00:11,710
and gain powerful partners

00:00:11,710 --> 00:00:15,147
to start, grow, or save
their businesses.

00:00:15,147 --> 00:00:16,982
Who wants a drink?
You're gonna need a drink.

00:00:16,982 --> 00:00:19,351
Saliva goes down,
and they suck it up.

00:00:19,351 --> 00:00:21,253
If the sharks hear
a great idea,

00:00:21,253 --> 00:00:24,290
they're ready to invest
using their own money.

00:00:24,290 --> 00:00:25,991
I'll offer you
a million dollars.

00:00:25,991 --> 00:00:29,128
I may consider going in
with big shark daddy here.

00:00:29,128 --> 00:00:31,564
And they'll fight each other
for a piece of the action.

00:00:31,564 --> 00:00:34,934
If you take that deal,
you get wiped out right now.

00:00:34,934 --> 00:00:36,535
You sold your soul.

00:00:36,535 --> 00:00:38,537
You, my friend,
become a millionaire.

00:00:38,537 --> 00:00:41,974
But first, the entrepreneurs
must convince a shark

00:00:41,974 --> 00:00:44,310
to invest the full amount
they're asking for,

00:00:44,310 --> 00:00:46,145
or they'll walk away
with nothing.

00:00:46,145 --> 00:00:47,646
An engineer that comes
on national tv

00:00:47,646 --> 00:00:49,481
and can't do their math--
That's not good.

00:00:49,481 --> 00:00:52,318
It's sink...
my--My--My--That was--
That was--

00:00:52,318 --> 00:00:53,652
or swim.

00:00:53,652 --> 00:00:55,287
Okay, kiddies, time for you
to leave the shark tank.

00:00:55,287 --> 00:00:57,256
This could get very ugly.

00:00:57,256 --> 00:00:59,358
♪♪♪

00:00:59,358 --> 00:01:02,027
Who are the sharks?

00:01:02,027 --> 00:01:05,898
They're self-made millionaire
and billionaire investors

00:01:05,898 --> 00:01:08,167
who are entrepreneurs
themselves.

00:01:09,602 --> 00:01:12,271
Kevin O'Leary
is a venture capitalist

00:01:12,271 --> 00:01:16,175
who turned a $10,000 loan
into a software business

00:01:16,175 --> 00:01:19,945
worth $4.2 billion.

00:01:19,945 --> 00:01:22,348
Lori Greiner,
the queen of qvc,

00:01:22,348 --> 00:01:24,149
holds over a hundred patents

00:01:24,149 --> 00:01:26,385
and has launched
over 300 products,

00:01:26,385 --> 00:01:28,187
grossing over
a half a billion dollars

00:01:28,187 --> 00:01:29,755
in retail sales.

00:01:29,755 --> 00:01:32,858
Daymond John is a fashion mogul
and branding expert

00:01:32,858 --> 00:01:35,160
who grew
his homemade clothing line

00:01:35,160 --> 00:01:38,897
into the globally recognized
fashion brand Fubu.

00:01:38,897 --> 00:01:41,900
Robert Herjavec, the son
of an immigrant factory worker,

00:01:41,900 --> 00:01:43,936
is now a technology mogul

00:01:43,936 --> 00:01:45,871
who sold
his first internet companies

00:01:45,871 --> 00:01:49,375
for over $350 million.

00:01:49,375 --> 00:01:51,277
And Mark Cuban,

00:01:51,277 --> 00:01:54,179
notorious
billionaire entrepreneur

00:01:54,179 --> 00:01:56,649
and the outspoken owner
of the Dallas Mavericks.

00:02:05,391 --> 00:02:08,894
♪♪♪

00:02:08,894 --> 00:02:11,864
First into the shark tank
is Doug Marshall

00:02:11,864 --> 00:02:14,433
with the next generation
of face painting.

00:02:16,769 --> 00:02:17,936
(chuckles)

00:02:20,506 --> 00:02:23,208
Hello, sharks.
My name is Doug Marshall,

00:02:23,208 --> 00:02:25,077
and I'm the creator
and owner

00:02:25,077 --> 00:02:27,012
of the Game Face company.

00:02:27,012 --> 00:02:31,250
We are here seeking
an investment of $450,000...

00:02:31,250 --> 00:02:32,651
damn.

00:02:32,651 --> 00:02:37,189
For a 25% equity stake
in the Game Face company.

00:02:37,189 --> 00:02:40,826
The Game Face
is a patented product

00:02:40,826 --> 00:02:42,828
that has revolutionized

00:02:42,828 --> 00:02:47,132
the face-painting, makeup,
and costume mask industry.

00:02:47,132 --> 00:02:50,869
Avid sport fans love
to paint their face,

00:02:50,869 --> 00:02:53,639
and kids of all ages
love trick-or-treating

00:02:53,639 --> 00:02:56,108
and dressing up
for halloween.

00:02:56,108 --> 00:02:57,876
My son here, will,

00:02:57,876 --> 00:02:59,945
is dressed up
for a maverick game

00:02:59,945 --> 00:03:02,514
if he could only score
on some tickets.

00:03:03,749 --> 00:03:05,784
And Katie, my daughter,

00:03:05,784 --> 00:03:08,087
is dressed up
as a butterfly girl.

00:03:08,087 --> 00:03:11,523
I would like to give
each of you a face...

00:03:11,523 --> 00:03:13,492
I love it when we get
free stuff.

00:03:13,492 --> 00:03:14,827
(Lori laughs)

00:03:14,827 --> 00:03:18,063
The faces are one size
trimmed to fit.

00:03:18,063 --> 00:03:20,833
I'm sporting
the Patriot face right now.

00:03:22,134 --> 00:03:23,802
Kevin, what face
are you sporting?

00:03:23,802 --> 00:03:26,672
(Lori laughs)
Mr. Wonderful's face.
Always smiling.

00:03:26,672 --> 00:03:29,708
I would like to give you
a tiger face.
Ooh!

00:03:29,708 --> 00:03:32,745
Thank you, Doug.
Lori, this is
an exotic mask face.

00:03:32,745 --> 00:03:34,113
(laughing)
This skeleton face

00:03:34,113 --> 00:03:35,948
May do just
the right thing for you.

00:03:35,948 --> 00:03:37,249
(Robert) Oh, that's so
perfect for you, Kevin.
I like that.

00:03:37,249 --> 00:03:38,617
That is perfect.

00:03:38,617 --> 00:03:40,185
Over the past
year and a half,

00:03:40,185 --> 00:03:43,188
all of our faces
have been wash-Away faces,

00:03:43,188 --> 00:03:44,523
much like a tattoo.

00:03:44,523 --> 00:03:47,159
So, we have had inquiries,
and people say,

00:03:47,159 --> 00:03:48,894
"Well, why couldn't I
wear a face

00:03:48,894 --> 00:03:50,996
and then just be able
to take it off?"

00:03:50,996 --> 00:03:55,734
so, if I can grab a--
an edge here

00:03:55,734 --> 00:03:57,569
of this face,

00:03:57,569 --> 00:04:01,440
and as I peel away...

00:04:01,440 --> 00:04:04,510
you can see that I'm not
having to wash it.
Wow!

00:04:04,510 --> 00:04:05,911
"Mission: Impossible."

00:04:05,911 --> 00:04:08,013
(Lori) so it's
a one-time use, Doug?

00:04:08,013 --> 00:04:09,348
Yes.

00:04:09,348 --> 00:04:11,750
But it's Peel off,
as opposed to wash off?

00:04:11,750 --> 00:04:13,952
Right.
(Robert) It's incredible.

00:04:13,952 --> 00:04:16,688
And it's--It's very
comfortable to wear.

00:04:16,688 --> 00:04:18,290
I mean... (mouth full)
You can...

00:04:18,290 --> 00:04:20,058
what?
Eat it? (laughs)
You can just eat it?

00:04:20,058 --> 00:04:22,361
Why?
Is that just a nasty habit,
or are you trying to show us--

00:04:22,361 --> 00:04:24,797
It's made with vegetable dyes,
and it's all water-based,

00:04:24,797 --> 00:04:26,432
and it's very safe
for kids.

00:04:26,432 --> 00:04:29,168
Let's go to the economics.
Tell us about the business,

00:04:29,168 --> 00:04:30,969
your revenues, your costs.

00:04:30,969 --> 00:04:32,438
We're in our fifth year
of business.

00:04:32,438 --> 00:04:34,440
And let me preface this--
This is a part-time job

00:04:34,440 --> 00:04:35,874
for me and my wife.

00:04:35,874 --> 00:04:38,477
And we literally have an office
above our garage,

00:04:38,477 --> 00:04:40,112
and we ship
out of our garage.

00:04:40,112 --> 00:04:43,649
Our first year, we did
$6,700 worth of sales,

00:04:43,649 --> 00:04:45,484
and last year,
we did $102,000.

00:04:45,484 --> 00:04:48,520
We anticipate doing $105,000
this year.

00:04:48,520 --> 00:04:52,191
$102,000,
and you are valuing

00:04:52,191 --> 00:04:56,395
that you you have a part-time
$1.8 million company...

00:04:56,395 --> 00:04:57,930
yes.
In your attic.

00:04:57,930 --> 00:04:59,598
Why are you worth
$1.8 million?

00:04:59,598 --> 00:05:03,769
Well, first of all, we haven't
even tapped into the big box.

00:05:03,769 --> 00:05:06,138
We have about 400 customers
that are all retail,

00:05:06,138 --> 00:05:07,873
small mom-and-pop shops.

00:05:07,873 --> 00:05:10,042
We have
licensed ncaa teams.

00:05:10,042 --> 00:05:11,677
We have a local license--

00:05:11,677 --> 00:05:13,979
Texas tech, tcu,
and a&amp;m.

00:05:13,979 --> 00:05:16,482
What does it cost you to make?
What do you sell 'em for?

00:05:16,482 --> 00:05:18,484
So we wholesale them
for $2.50,

00:05:18,484 --> 00:05:22,488
and our cost will range
from 25 cents to 60 cents.

00:05:22,488 --> 00:05:24,022
It's all volume-driven.

00:05:24,022 --> 00:05:26,425
Great margin.
Only our designs
are all retailed

00:05:26,425 --> 00:05:27,960
for $4.99.
(Daymond) It is
a great margin.

00:05:27,960 --> 00:05:29,294
(Mark) So you're paying
10 per--
It's a $5 item.

00:05:29,294 --> 00:05:32,798
And, Doug, on the $102,000
that you sold last year,

00:05:32,798 --> 00:05:34,967
how much money did you
make on that?

00:05:34,967 --> 00:05:38,070
We made $32,000.

00:05:38,070 --> 00:05:40,138
The numbers just don't add up.

00:05:40,138 --> 00:05:43,075
Okay, kiddies, it's time
for you to leave the shark tank.

00:05:43,075 --> 00:05:45,777
Your daddy's asked
for $1.8 million value

00:05:45,777 --> 00:05:48,780
on his company.
This could get very ugly.

00:05:48,780 --> 00:05:50,816
Yeah, we're gonna put on
some ugly faces...
Bye, guys.

00:05:50,816 --> 00:05:52,718
And, uh, talk to your Dad.
(laughs)

00:05:52,718 --> 00:05:54,052
Are there competitors?

00:05:54,052 --> 00:05:55,854
There's no competitors.
Okay.

00:05:55,854 --> 00:05:57,422
And there can't be
any competitors,

00:05:57,422 --> 00:05:58,657
because of our patent.

00:05:58,657 --> 00:06:00,559
(Robert) But--But, Doug,
that can't be true.

00:06:00,559 --> 00:06:02,694
I've bought stickers--

00:06:02,694 --> 00:06:03,962
the key is full face.
The key is full face.

00:06:03,962 --> 00:06:05,264
Full face.
Full face.

00:06:05,264 --> 00:06:06,765
What's your full-time job,
Doug?

00:06:06,765 --> 00:06:08,300
I work for xerox
selling copiers.

00:06:08,300 --> 00:06:11,303
You've got these big margins.
It's working for you.
Yeah.

00:06:11,303 --> 00:06:13,972
Why still sell copiers
instead of do this full-time?

00:06:13,972 --> 00:06:15,741
Well, we've got two kids.
We got--

00:06:15,741 --> 00:06:17,442
We got into
the real estate bust

00:06:17,442 --> 00:06:19,244
in east texas.
Okay, so you gotta
pay the bills, basically.

00:06:19,244 --> 00:06:21,980
I gotta pay the bills.
What's the $450,000 for?

00:06:21,980 --> 00:06:24,449
$300,000 would get me
on a salary

00:06:24,449 --> 00:06:25,918
for the next three years,

00:06:25,918 --> 00:06:28,954
get us going
with the licenses.

00:06:28,954 --> 00:06:30,722
We want to get nba.

00:06:30,722 --> 00:06:32,090
(Daymond) one second,
one second. Doug.

00:06:32,090 --> 00:06:33,792
You just basically said,

00:06:33,792 --> 00:06:38,330
"I want $100,000 a year
for 3 years."

00:06:38,330 --> 00:06:40,465
I think that's absurd.

00:06:40,465 --> 00:06:43,235
I-I didn't make any money
from my business for nine years.

00:06:44,937 --> 00:06:46,838
I'm out.

00:06:49,775 --> 00:06:52,711
Doug, I-I really like
the product.

00:06:52,711 --> 00:06:55,013
But I gotta tell you,
when you said,

00:06:55,013 --> 00:06:57,416
"I'm gonna take a $100,000
salary for the next 3 years,

00:06:57,416 --> 00:06:59,318
and that's why I need
an investment"--

00:06:59,318 --> 00:07:01,453
to guarantee that
for the next three years,

00:07:01,453 --> 00:07:05,023
with all due respect, you gotta
be friggin' kidding me.

00:07:06,825 --> 00:07:10,062
When I started my business,
do you know how many years

00:07:10,062 --> 00:07:11,530
before I made $100,000?

00:07:11,530 --> 00:07:13,298
And you're coming here
and asking me

00:07:13,298 --> 00:07:15,267
to guarantee that for you?

00:07:15,267 --> 00:07:18,103
This could turn water
into gold,

00:07:18,103 --> 00:07:19,838
but I'm sorry, my friend.

00:07:19,838 --> 00:07:22,608
I wouldn't want to invest
alongside with you.

00:07:22,608 --> 00:07:23,642
I'm out.

00:07:23,642 --> 00:07:26,111
Okay.

00:07:27,613 --> 00:07:30,248
(Mark) What are you gonna
use the money for, Doug?

00:07:30,248 --> 00:07:34,086
To get me to go full-time
and license acquisitions.

00:07:34,086 --> 00:07:35,887
(Kevin) Doug, let me solve
that problem for you right now.

00:07:35,887 --> 00:07:37,289
Here's a deal for you.

00:07:37,289 --> 00:07:40,826
I'll give you $450,000.
Here's how I'll do it.

00:07:40,826 --> 00:07:43,562
I'll give you $150,000
of it

00:07:43,562 --> 00:07:45,497
for 30% of your company.

00:07:45,497 --> 00:07:47,332
The other $300,000
you've asked for,

00:07:47,332 --> 00:07:49,234
I'll give to you as a loan.

00:07:49,234 --> 00:07:51,703
And I'm going to put
a 25-cent royalty

00:07:51,703 --> 00:07:55,474
on every mask until I get
my $150,000 back.

00:07:55,474 --> 00:07:57,876
(Lori) I-I would like
to make you an offer--

00:07:57,876 --> 00:08:01,146
the $450,000.

00:08:01,146 --> 00:08:04,082
But I'd like Mark
to go in with me.

00:08:04,082 --> 00:08:06,652
And for 40% stake.

00:08:06,652 --> 00:08:10,856
But I can immediately
get you into all the licensing

00:08:10,856 --> 00:08:14,126
and into retailers
all over the country.

00:08:14,126 --> 00:08:16,828
I would like to hear from Mark.
He's been awfully quiet.
(Lori) Yes.

00:08:16,828 --> 00:08:18,597
Mark, what do you have to say?
Um...

00:08:18,597 --> 00:08:19,965
I gotta tell you--

00:08:19,965 --> 00:08:21,400
So, when I first
took over the mavs,

00:08:21,400 --> 00:08:22,934
no one would go
to the games.

00:08:22,934 --> 00:08:25,137
Right? I-I literally
had to hand out tickets.

00:08:25,137 --> 00:08:27,039
And one of the promotions
I ran was--

00:08:27,039 --> 00:08:28,840
and it's running
to this day--

00:08:28,840 --> 00:08:31,043
That if you come
to a mavs game

00:08:31,043 --> 00:08:33,512
with your face and/or body
fully painted

00:08:33,512 --> 00:08:35,347
in mavs colors,
we're gonna have a contest,

00:08:35,347 --> 00:08:37,516
and we'll pick the craziest
and give you free seats.

00:08:37,516 --> 00:08:39,184
Yeah.
And it's such a mess.

00:08:39,184 --> 00:08:41,286
There's paint.
There's mess everywhere.
Yes.

00:08:41,286 --> 00:08:44,656
So I-I can relate.
It's a great option.
Yeah.

00:08:44,656 --> 00:08:46,625
Okay, here's the offer
I'll make. Um...

00:08:46,625 --> 00:08:48,560
I'll offer you
a million dollars...

00:08:50,095 --> 00:08:52,230
Yowza!

00:08:52,230 --> 00:08:54,132
For the entire company.

00:08:54,132 --> 00:08:56,635
Whoa.

00:08:56,635 --> 00:08:58,837
Included
in that million dollars

00:08:58,837 --> 00:09:02,507
is a salary to you
of $80,000 a year

00:09:02,507 --> 00:09:04,476
for five years.

00:09:04,476 --> 00:09:06,144
Lori, I'll bring you in
if you'd like--

00:09:06,144 --> 00:09:07,846
if you'd like to come in,
I'm happy to bring you in.

00:09:07,846 --> 00:09:10,716
I'm in on Mark's offer.
I like it.

00:09:10,716 --> 00:09:13,985
(Kevin) You understand
what's happening to you, right?

00:09:13,985 --> 00:09:16,455
If you take that deal,
you get wiped out

00:09:16,455 --> 00:09:18,457
right now.

00:09:18,457 --> 00:09:21,193
You gave up your future.
You sold your soul.

00:09:21,193 --> 00:09:23,462
You own nothing.

00:09:27,065 --> 00:09:30,035
♪♪♪

00:09:39,834 --> 00:09:41,336
Two sharks are out.

00:09:41,336 --> 00:09:44,472
Doug has two offers
on the table--

00:09:44,472 --> 00:09:46,541
$450,000 for a 30% stake

00:09:46,541 --> 00:09:48,410
and a 25-cent royalty
from Kevin,

00:09:48,410 --> 00:09:51,379
and $1 million
for 100% of the company

00:09:51,379 --> 00:09:53,748
from Mark and Lori.

00:09:53,748 --> 00:09:55,550
(Kevin) You understand
what's happening to you, right?

00:09:55,550 --> 00:09:58,787
If you take that deal,
you get wiped out right now.

00:09:58,787 --> 00:10:00,922
You gave up your future.
You sold your soul.

00:10:00,922 --> 00:10:02,357
You own nothing.

00:10:02,357 --> 00:10:04,159
You, my friend,
become a millionaire.

00:10:07,429 --> 00:10:09,164
Doug, I saw your soul
drift out of the shark tank.

00:10:09,164 --> 00:10:11,733
(mark laughs)
There it goes.

00:10:11,733 --> 00:10:13,134
(Lori laughs)
It could've been worth
$15 million, but no.

00:10:13,134 --> 00:10:15,337
That's exactly
what's happening.
(laughing)

00:10:15,337 --> 00:10:16,938
So, my offer makes
a lot more sense.

00:10:16,938 --> 00:10:18,940
I leave 70% of the upside
to you.

00:10:18,940 --> 00:10:20,942
It's perfect.

00:10:20,942 --> 00:10:24,312
I move lightning-Fast,
and I have all the connections.

00:10:24,312 --> 00:10:26,948
I think that mark
would be the right partner.

00:10:26,948 --> 00:10:31,553
With his abilities
and with mine together,

00:10:31,553 --> 00:10:33,555
this can become
an overnight sensation.

00:10:34,122 --> 00:10:36,791
So, Doug, when I started
my business,

00:10:36,791 --> 00:10:38,893
a guy came along,
offered me $5 million.

00:10:38,893 --> 00:10:41,963
It was more money
than I had ever dreamed of.

00:10:43,298 --> 00:10:46,034
I went home,
and I told my wife about it.

00:10:46,034 --> 00:10:48,770
And she looked at me
and she said,

00:10:48,770 --> 00:10:49,371
"I don't believe
you started this business

00:10:49,371 --> 00:10:51,172
"to work for somebody else
one day.

00:10:51,172 --> 00:10:53,775
I think you can make it
much bigger."

00:10:53,775 --> 00:10:56,011
I was shocked. We had car loans,
we had a huge mortgage.

00:10:56,011 --> 00:10:58,079
It was worth hundreds
of millions of dollars,

00:10:58,079 --> 00:11:00,648
and I hung on to it.

00:11:00,648 --> 00:11:01,216
It was the best decision
I ever made.

00:11:05,587 --> 00:11:07,155
What are you going to do?

00:11:10,525 --> 00:11:12,894
I would like to, uh,
talk to my family about it.

00:11:12,894 --> 00:11:14,295
Okay.

00:11:18,600 --> 00:11:21,469
Mark, partnered with Lori,
has offered us,

00:11:21,469 --> 00:11:23,805
uh, a million dollars...

00:11:23,805 --> 00:11:25,507
(laughs)
In order... (laughs)

